{
  "answer": "**Chapter 67 of the *Viṣṇu Smṛti* details the householder's daily *bali* (ritual food oblation) ceremony.** \n\nIt begins with preparations around the fire and oblations to Viṣṇu's forms (Vāsudeva etc.), major deities (Agni, Soma etc.), and the fire's svāhā, followed by *bali* offerings eastward of the fire and around the house to female deities (Ambā etc.), household guardians, directional deities and their attendants (Indra in east, Yama in south etc.), sky, diurnal/nocturnal spirits, and ancestors via *piṇḍa* (funeral cakes). It concludes with offerings to animals/outcastes, alms, and extensive rules on honoring *atithis* (unexpected Brāhmaṇa guests): their superiority, feeding priority after family dependents but before self, benefits equivalent to Vedic rites, and exclusions (e.g., locals, purpose-visitors).[^1]\n\n[^1]: *Viṣṇu Smṛti*, *Chapter 67*, [/works/unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8/67/translation/].",
